WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.475 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:02.475 --> 00:00:15.840 align:middle line:90%


00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:19.320 align:middle line:10%
>> This is Book Tours,
and I'm Corinne Edwards.

00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:22.530 align:middle line:10%
I'd like you to meet one of
the most important messengers

00:00:22.530 --> 00:00:25.530 align:middle line:10%
in publishing today,
important because the authors

00:00:25.530 --> 00:00:29.550 align:middle line:10%
on this show are dedicated to
your personal growth, to make

00:00:29.550 --> 00:00:33.660 align:middle line:10%
you happier, healthier,
to be the best you can be,

00:00:33.660 --> 00:00:37.920 align:middle line:10%
Dr. Andrew Weil, author of
"Eating Well for Optimum

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:39.150 align:middle line:10%
Health."

00:00:39.150 --> 00:00:42.390 align:middle line:84%
There are many books on diets
out there, and many of us

00:00:42.390 --> 00:00:44.580 align:middle line:90%
have tried them all.

00:00:44.580 --> 00:00:46.080 align:middle line:90%
What works?

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:49.920 align:middle line:84%
On the low carb diets, even a
green pepper becomes an enemy.

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:51.330 align:middle line:90%
I'm confused.

00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:53.640 align:middle line:84%
But Dr. Andrew Weil,
the renowned author

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:56.160 align:middle line:84%
of "Eating Well
for Optimum Health"

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:58.350 align:middle line:90%
is here to help us today.

00:00:58.350 --> 00:01:01.470 align:middle line:84%
Andrew, what about
all these new diets?

00:01:01.470 --> 00:01:03.720 align:middle line:84%
>> I think it's crazier out
there than I ever remember

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:05.280 align:middle line:90%
in my lifetime.

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:07.950 align:middle line:90%
People are really confused.

00:01:07.950 --> 00:01:10.770 align:middle line:10%
I think most of these diets
I would consider extreme.

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:13.410 align:middle line:84%
They're asking us to make
drastic rearrangements of fat,

00:01:13.410 --> 00:01:15.360 align:middle line:90%
carbohydrate, and protein.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:16.460 align:middle line:90%
I don't think that's wise.

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:18.840 align:middle line:84%
And certainly not wise as a
long-term eating strategy,

00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:23.370 align:middle line:84%
although, many of them will
work as short-term crash diets.

00:01:23.370 --> 00:01:28.310 align:middle line:84%
>> I sat next to a lady in
the beauty shop yesterday,

00:01:28.310 --> 00:01:31.890 align:middle line:84%
and I remember her
from maybe a year ago.

00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:36.380 align:middle line:84%
She has lost 100 pounds
on the Atkins diet.

00:01:36.380 --> 00:01:38.960 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, great, now it's a
problem she's got is how is she

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:42.085 align:middle line:84%
going to transition off of
this onto a way of eating

00:01:42.085 --> 00:01:44.210 align:middle line:84%
that's going to work for
long-term health because I

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:47.420 align:middle line:84%
don't think following an Atkins
diet is good for the long-term

00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:49.350 align:middle line:90%
health of your kidneys or liver.

00:01:49.350 --> 00:01:52.970 align:middle line:84%
So if she goes off it, she's
going to regain all the weight,

00:01:52.970 --> 00:01:55.140 align:middle line:84%
and she can't stay
on this long term.

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:56.060 align:middle line:90%
So that's the dilemma.

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:57.140 align:middle line:90%
>> She says she can.

00:01:57.140 --> 00:02:00.200 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, because eating
that much protein is really

00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:01.820 align:middle line:84%
unhealthy for your
liver and kidneys.

00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:05.210 align:middle line:84%
And also, people on this diet
are often very unconscious

00:02:05.210 --> 00:02:07.490 align:middle line:84%
about the kind and amount
of fat that they eat.

00:02:07.490 --> 00:02:10.280 align:middle line:84%
So again, it's
over the long term,

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:12.860 align:middle line:84%
this is not a good way to
maintain physical health

00:02:12.860 --> 00:02:14.115 align:middle line:90%
or mental well-being.

00:02:14.115 --> 00:02:16.490 align:middle line:84%
>> All right, what about the
fact that they're saying now

00:02:16.490 --> 00:02:19.845 align:middle line:84%
that some people are actually
allergic to carbohydrates?

00:02:19.845 --> 00:02:21.470 align:middle line:84%
>> I don't think
that's the right term.

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:23.660 align:middle line:84%
I think there is
carbohydrate sensitivity,

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:27.710 align:middle line:84%
and maybe 25% to 30% of the
population is in that category.

00:02:27.710 --> 00:02:29.210 align:middle line:84%
If you're carbohydrate
sensitive,

00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:30.627 align:middle line:84%
I don't think that
means you never

00:02:30.627 --> 00:02:33.470 align:middle line:84%
eat carbohydrate or the
carbohydrate is the enemy.

00:02:33.470 --> 00:02:35.570 align:middle line:84%
I do think it means you
need to pay attention

00:02:35.570 --> 00:02:38.630 align:middle line:84%
to the differences in different
kinds of carbohydrates,

00:02:38.630 --> 00:02:41.510 align:middle line:84%
that, for example, that
pasta is better than bread

00:02:41.510 --> 00:02:44.540 align:middle line:84%
because it's digested more
slowly, that you can reduce

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:48.170 align:middle line:84%
the impact of pasta even more
by cooking it really al dente so

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:50.210 align:middle line:84%
that it's chewy and
firm, that there's

00:02:50.210 --> 00:02:53.510 align:middle line:84%
a big difference between dense,
dark, chewy, grainy peasant

00:02:53.510 --> 00:02:55.550 align:middle line:90%
bread and white, fluffy bread.

00:02:55.550 --> 00:02:58.160 align:middle line:84%
You know, there are
differences in carbohydrates.

00:02:58.160 --> 00:02:59.990 align:middle line:90%
>> So what happens like--

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:04.190 align:middle line:84%
you talk about whole wheat
bread against white bread.

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:06.500 align:middle line:84%
Well, first of all, you say
never put it in your mouth.

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:08.420 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, the problem is that
most whole wheat bread is

00:03:08.420 --> 00:03:10.880 align:middle line:84%
indistinguishable from white
bread in terms of its impact

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:13.525 align:middle line:84%
on blood sugar because, even
though the grains are whole,

00:03:13.525 --> 00:03:15.650 align:middle line:84%
they've been milled into
these very fine particles.

00:03:15.650 --> 00:03:18.530 align:middle line:84%
That's the main determinant
of how fast it's digested.

00:03:18.530 --> 00:03:20.420 align:middle line:84%
But there's a
difference, as I said,

00:03:20.420 --> 00:03:22.820 align:middle line:84%
the old-fashioned, peasant
bread in which was actually

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:27.470 align:middle line:84%
cracked grains, it's course,
that has a much, much less

00:03:27.470 --> 00:03:29.840 align:middle line:84%
of an impact on blood
sugar and insulin levels

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:31.640 align:middle line:84%
and even carbohydrate
sensitive people

00:03:31.640 --> 00:03:33.230 align:middle line:90%
can eat it in moderation.

00:03:33.230 --> 00:03:36.650 align:middle line:84%
>> What about what about the
fact that they're now saying,

00:03:36.650 --> 00:03:39.297 align:middle line:84%
on these diets, now let's
throw the zone-- in there.

00:03:39.297 --> 00:03:40.130 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, yeah, good.

00:03:40.130 --> 00:03:42.230 align:middle line:84%
>> You can throw
Pritikin in there?

00:03:42.230 --> 00:03:44.260 align:middle line:84%
What about-- they're
saying now, for example,

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:48.930 align:middle line:84%
Pritikin says fruits and
vegetables, almost no protein,

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:51.070 align:middle line:90%
and almost no carbs.

00:03:51.070 --> 00:03:55.530 align:middle line:84%
>> The Pritikin good diet is
one of these ultra low fat diets

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:56.760 align:middle line:90%
along with Ornish.

00:03:56.760 --> 00:03:58.410 align:middle line:84%
And I think the
problem of those diets

00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:00.900 align:middle line:84%
is, first of all, is you
get fat so low, food really

00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:02.023 align:middle line:90%
becomes uninteresting.

00:04:02.023 --> 00:04:04.440 align:middle line:84%
And I think most of us aren't
going to stay on those diets

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:07.020 align:middle line:84%
unless there's a very
strong medical motivation.

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:09.030 align:middle line:84%
But another problem is
that these very low fat

00:04:09.030 --> 00:04:13.440 align:middle line:84%
diets worsen deficiency
of omega-3 fatty acids,

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:16.980 align:middle line:84%
the ones in fish and nuts
and some soy products.

00:04:16.980 --> 00:04:18.720 align:middle line:84%
You've got to have
these, and most of us

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:19.500 align:middle line:90%
are deficient in them.

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:21.060 align:middle line:84%
And I think you're
in greater danger

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:23.070 align:middle line:90%
on these very low fat diets.

00:04:23.070 --> 00:04:26.340 align:middle line:84%
One of the crazy ideas I hear
from the low carbohydrate diet

00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:28.980 align:middle line:84%
is that you shouldn't eat
carrots or beets because these

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:30.360 align:middle line:90%
are supposed to have too much--

00:04:30.360 --> 00:04:30.840 align:middle line:90%
>> Green pepper.

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:32.360 align:middle line:84%
>> Sugar in it--
or green pepper.

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:33.600 align:middle line:90%
This is crazy.

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:37.073 align:middle line:84%
In order to eat enough carrots
to disturb blood sugar,

00:04:37.073 --> 00:04:38.490 align:middle line:84%
you'd have to eat
probably 1 pound

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:40.390 align:middle line:90%
and 1/2 at a single sitting.

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:41.190 align:middle line:90%
>> A real rabbit.

00:04:41.190 --> 00:04:41.520 align:middle line:90%
>> Really.

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:43.290 align:middle line:84%
Hard to tell people
not the carrots

00:04:43.290 --> 00:04:46.140 align:middle line:84%
is silly because carrots
are full of compounds

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:48.480 align:middle line:84%
that protect us against
cancer, that are really

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:49.780 align:middle line:90%
good for long-term health.

00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:52.800 align:middle line:84%
So I think that these writers
have pieces of the truth,

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:54.620 align:middle line:90%
but then it's distorted.

00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:57.170 align:middle line:84%
>> All right, let's go to
some of the other theories.

00:04:57.170 --> 00:04:59.700 align:middle line:84%
This is a very
well-known nutritionist

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:05.370 align:middle line:84%
I heard about who said, what the
secret of balancing your blood

00:05:05.370 --> 00:05:09.480 align:middle line:84%
sugar so that you don't
have this rush of insulin

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:11.760 align:middle line:90%
is to not mix things.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:17.510 align:middle line:84%
Like, you should put protein
with vegetables and carbs--

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:18.595 align:middle line:90%
and not eat carbs.

00:05:18.595 --> 00:05:19.470 align:middle line:90%
>> I have heard this.

00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:20.490 align:middle line:90%
I've read this theory.

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:22.500 align:middle line:84%
I think this business
of food combining

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:24.210 align:middle line:90%
is a very individual matter.

00:05:24.210 --> 00:05:26.250 align:middle line:84%
Some combinations don't
agree with some people.

00:05:26.250 --> 00:05:27.990 align:middle line:84%
I don't think there's
general rules.

00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:29.850 align:middle line:84%
Protein and carbohydrate
are naturally

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:32.490 align:middle line:84%
mixed in beans and
grains, which have

00:05:32.490 --> 00:05:34.410 align:middle line:84%
sustained life in
a lot of cultures

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:36.990 align:middle line:90%
throughout a lot of history.

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:39.630 align:middle line:84%
I don't think it's any
mystery why Americans are fat.

00:05:39.630 --> 00:05:41.580 align:middle line:84%
Americans are fat because
they eat too much,

00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:43.663 align:middle line:84%
and they eat too much of
the wrong kinds of foods,

00:05:43.663 --> 00:05:45.090 align:middle line:84%
so they don't get
enough activity.

00:05:45.090 --> 00:05:46.450 align:middle line:90%
They eat too much in two ways.

00:05:46.450 --> 00:05:48.390 align:middle line:84%
They eat portions
that are too big,

00:05:48.390 --> 00:05:49.740 align:middle line:90%
and they eat too frequently.

00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:53.010 align:middle line:84%
And I think these trends have
increased in my lifetime.

00:05:53.010 --> 00:05:57.120 align:middle line:84%
When I was a kid, nobody
was eating Big Gulps

00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:59.820 align:middle line:84%
of soft drinks and
buckets of popcorn

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:02.622 align:middle line:84%
in movie theaters and
oversized muffins.

00:06:02.622 --> 00:06:04.080 align:middle line:84%
People from other
cultures who come

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:06.810 align:middle line:84%
to our restaurants, their eyes
bug out at the size of portions

00:06:06.810 --> 00:06:07.610 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:06:07.610 --> 00:06:08.820 align:middle line:84%
And they get right
into it because when

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:10.862 align:middle line:84%
you put that quantity of
food in front of people,

00:06:10.862 --> 00:06:11.827 align:middle line:90%
they go for it.

00:06:11.827 --> 00:06:13.410 align:middle line:84%
But I think all this
has gotten worse.

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:16.200 align:middle line:84%
And in terms of inactivity,
I think major factors here

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:20.370 align:middle line:84%
are television, computers,
video games, which

00:06:20.370 --> 00:06:22.830 align:middle line:84%
have sucked more and
more young people

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:26.190 align:middle line:84%
into sedentary lifestyles,
and automobiles, which I think

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:28.783 align:middle line:90%
have really sabotaged walking.

00:06:28.783 --> 00:06:30.450 align:middle line:84%
So I think I don't
think you need a book

00:06:30.450 --> 00:06:31.877 align:middle line:90%
to figure out why we're fat.

00:06:31.877 --> 00:06:33.960 align:middle line:84%
And I also don't think you
need a book or a theory

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:35.377 align:middle line:84%
to figure out what
to do about it.

00:06:35.377 --> 00:06:38.250 align:middle line:84%
You want to eat less, and you
want to increase activity.

00:06:38.250 --> 00:06:41.370 align:middle line:84%
And you also want to eat
the right kinds of foods.

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:43.710 align:middle line:84%
I think that this new
information about carbohydrates

00:06:43.710 --> 00:06:47.220 align:middle line:84%
is very important because not
all carbohydrates are equal,

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:50.400 align:middle line:84%
and some people are very
sensitive to the weight gaining

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:53.280 align:middle line:84%
effects of refined
carbohydrates.

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:57.410 align:middle line:84%
>> While I had you on this show
about a year and a half ago.

00:06:57.410 --> 00:06:59.720 align:middle line:90%
You're much slimmer now.

00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:00.630 align:middle line:90%
What did you do?

00:07:00.630 --> 00:07:01.547 align:middle line:90%
>> OK, first of all--

00:07:01.547 --> 00:07:02.630 align:middle line:90%
>> You weren't fat before.

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:04.890 align:middle line:90%
>> My body type is--

00:07:04.890 --> 00:07:06.140 align:middle line:90%
I have this kind of body type.

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:08.900 align:middle line:84%
I am never going to
be svelte and skinny.

00:07:08.900 --> 00:07:10.550 align:middle line:84%
I think it's
important for people

00:07:10.550 --> 00:07:13.700 align:middle line:84%
to realize that body type
is genetically determined.

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:15.710 align:middle line:84%
We don't think we can
control our height,

00:07:15.710 --> 00:07:18.320 align:middle line:84%
and we don't have much more
power to control our body type.

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:21.110 align:middle line:84%
And your body wants to
be at a certain weight.

00:07:21.110 --> 00:07:23.150 align:middle line:84%
I think we're made
crazy in this culture

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:26.360 align:middle line:84%
by being bombarded with all
these messages from the fashion

00:07:26.360 --> 00:07:29.930 align:middle line:84%
and entertainment industries
about an ideal body type that's

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:32.840 align:middle line:90%
an impossibility for most of us.

00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:37.040 align:middle line:84%
I work to keep myself in good
shape by being very active.

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:41.030 align:middle line:84%
When I'm home, I either
walk every day, I swim, or I

00:07:41.030 --> 00:07:43.490 align:middle line:84%
bicycle, or some
combination of all of that,

00:07:43.490 --> 00:07:44.980 align:middle line:90%
and I get daily activity.

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:46.320 align:middle line:90%
And I also watch what I eat.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:49.490 align:middle line:84%
I have found that, for
myself, that just cutting out

00:07:49.490 --> 00:07:52.460 align:middle line:84%
bread or cutting down on bread
has been a great strategy

00:07:52.460 --> 00:07:55.310 align:middle line:90%
for controlling my weight.

00:07:55.310 --> 00:07:58.670 align:middle line:84%
But it's worth remembering
that we could as easily have

00:07:58.670 --> 00:08:01.160 align:middle line:84%
been born into a
culture or a time

00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:03.230 align:middle line:84%
where skinny people were
thought to be sexually

00:08:03.230 --> 00:08:04.460 align:middle line:90%
unattractive and unhealthy.

00:08:04.460 --> 00:08:07.040 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I can't stand
skinny men myself.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:09.000 align:middle line:84%
I like a man with a
little bit of heft to him.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.310 align:middle line:90%
But women particularly, Andrew.

00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:12.110 align:middle line:90%
>> I know.

00:08:12.110 --> 00:08:13.140 align:middle line:90%
I am aware.

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:15.380 align:middle line:90%
I am aware.

00:08:15.380 --> 00:08:16.940 align:middle line:84%
But I think this
is very damaging

00:08:16.940 --> 00:08:20.990 align:middle line:84%
because most people can't
attain this kind of ideal that's

00:08:20.990 --> 00:08:22.140 align:middle line:90%
put out there.

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:24.770 align:middle line:84%
I also think that, if
you're not morbidly obese--

00:08:24.770 --> 00:08:27.370 align:middle line:84%
and we all know morbid
obesity when we see it.

00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:29.210 align:middle line:90%
>> What is morbid obesity?

00:08:29.210 --> 00:08:32.780 align:middle line:84%
>> Greater than-- significantly
greater than 20% over

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:35.510 align:middle line:84%
your, what your
body fat should be.

00:08:35.510 --> 00:08:38.030 align:middle line:84%
But you know we all know
people whose walking is

00:08:38.030 --> 00:08:40.669 align:middle line:90%
impaired by how big they are.

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:43.890 align:middle line:84%
If you're not in that category,
and you are overweight,

00:08:43.890 --> 00:08:47.670 align:middle line:84%
I don't think that there's any
necessary consequence on health

00:08:47.670 --> 00:08:50.660 align:middle line:84%
or longevity if you keep
yourself fit and healthy,

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:55.070 align:middle line:84%
meaning that you get adequate
exercise, and you eat well.

00:08:55.070 --> 00:08:57.470 align:middle line:84%
So I think I think that
the obsession with leanness

00:08:57.470 --> 00:09:01.010 align:middle line:84%
has even distorted our
medical information.

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:03.830 align:middle line:84%
>> Do you think that men
really like skinny women?

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:05.280 align:middle line:84%
Well, I can only
speak for myself.

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:06.320 align:middle line:90%
I don't.

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:08.750 align:middle line:84%
I don't like people
that look skeletal.

00:09:08.750 --> 00:09:10.970 align:middle line:90%
I also like some heft.

